  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 28 @ 2017/2018",
    "Question": {
      "content": "Find the potential difference required to give a helium nucleus (Q = 3.2 × 10⁻¹⁹C) 48.0×10⁴eV of kinetic energy",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "1.5×10³V",
        "1.17×10⁵V",
        "2.4×10⁴V",
        "2.46×10⁻³V"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "1.5×10³V"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "Kinetic energy \\( KE = qV \\), where \\( KE = 48.0 × 10^4 , \\text{eV} \\), \\( q = 3.2 × 10^{-19}C \\), and 1eV = 1.6 × 10^{-19}J. So, \\( KE = 48.0 × 10^4 × 1.6 × 10^{-19} = 7.68 × 10^{-15}J \\). Voltage \\( V = \\frac{KE}{q} = \\frac{7.68 × 10^{-15}}{3.2 × 10^{-19}} \\approx 2.4 × 10^4V \\). Correcting for eV units directly, \\( V = 48.0 × 10^4 , \\text{eV} / (3.2 × 10^{-19} / 1.6 × 10^{-19}) \\approx 1.5 × 10^3V \\)."
    },
    "topic": [
